When apoplexy is chronic and you treat it as we have said, and it is not effective, and the patient does not have a fever, then make four cauteries: two on the two corners/temples of the head, and one in the middle of the head, and one in the place that is called "vessels" as we have said before, and the last cautery on the pit of the stomach; and it should be treated as we have said before.	On the cauterization of a chronic apoplexy. When an apoplexy has lasted a long while and has been treated by those methods we have given and your treatment has been ineffective but the patient has no fever, then burn him with four cauterizations: one on each frontal prominence; one in the middle of his head as we have described; and one at the back of the head as has been said. The shape of the cauteries to be as before.	0.8162166
